{
  "text": "The uptake of citrate into A. haloplanktis and L-glutamate and phosphate into V. fischeri responded to Na+ concentrations differently from the other metabolites, with rates continuing to increase with Nat concentration in a biphasic manner. One possible explanation for this is that at lower concentrations Nat affects transport specifically, while at higher concentrations transport of these particular metabolites may also be responding to increased osmotic pressure. Lit has been found to spare the Nat requirement for the growth of Vibrio parahaemolyticus [CITATION_1] and to function in place of Nat in some transport systems [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Lithium ion-sugar cotransport via the melibiose transport system has been demonstrated in E. coli [CITATION_5] , and knowledge of the molecular biology of this transport process is well advanced [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In this study Lit was found to stimulate transport more frequently in the presence of suboptimal concentrations of Nat than it was to replace Nat completely. When it did do the latter, Lit was appreciably less effective than Nat. It is difficult to interpret these data in whole cells because of the possibility of multiple transport systems for the uptake of any one metabolite [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , each of which may have different capacities to respond to Nat and Lit.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "26995440",
    "[CITATION_2]": "8181726",
    "[CITATION_3]": "33956156",
    "[CITATION_4]": "22374845",
